author: National Geographic
description:
Surrounded by her friends and family, Sally Ride cemented her place in history on this day 42 years ago. 

Sally is now streaming on Disney+ and Hulu.
title: What happened on launch day, June 18, 1983? #SALLYfilm

author: National Geographic
description:
Once thriving across Florida’s prairies, fewer than 200 Florida grasshopper sparrows are known to exist in the wild—highlighting the devastation of their habitat. But what if they can be saved? Biologist Fabiola ‘Fabby’ Baeza-Tarin and an unexpected team unite to save the U.S.'s most endangered songbird in The Little Brown Bird.

Watch The Little Brown Bird now on Nat Geo's YouTube channel and discover more about the efforts to save this species: https://on.natgeo.com/BRYTS061825
title: Saving the U.S.'s most endangered songbird #LittleBrownBird

author: National Geographic
description: Join Zoe Saldaña and Nat Geo Explorer Dr. Bethany Ehlmann to talk all things space, and don’t miss Disney and Pixar's Elio, in theaters Friday.
title: Elio’s sense of wonder takes us to the stars 🌠 #Elio

author: National Geographic
description:
Ever wonder how Disney brings its most immersive experiences to life?

This National Geographic mini-episode, created in collaboration with Disney Cruise Line, takes you behind the scenes of their newest ship. Meet the visionary designers, performers, and puppeteers bringing characters like Moana, Te Fiti, and Tamatoa to life using cutting-edge materials and intense training. Step into a vibrant dining experience inspired by Disney and Pixar’s Coco and get an exclusive look at the eerie enchantment of the Haunted Mansion Parlor.

Watch the full episode of Magic of the Disney Treasure now streaming on @disneyplus and @hulu.

Want to dive deeper into Disney magic?
Watch Magic of Disney Lookout Cay at Lighthouse Point: https://on.natgeo.com/4leWejq

author: National Geographic
description:
Paid content for @debeers. Botswana’s Okavango Delta is one of the most photographed natural spaces in the world, but these stories are rarely told by those local to the area. Supported by De Beers and National Geographic through the Okavango Eternal partnership, a Motswana photographer is working to train and empower the next generation of storytellers.
